my boyfriend was cheating

06:49.109 --> 06:52.443
at Crazy Eights,
at Backgammon,

06:52.443 --> 06:53.844
and on his history quiz.

06:56.447 --> 06:58.619
Another case solved
by Darryl Parks!

07:06.697 --> 07:09.860
I am the elusive,
legendary Bigfoot,

07:09.860 --> 07:12.903
or Sasquatch
to my friends.

07:12.903 --> 07:15.035
Darryl Parks
even found me!

07:19.439 --> 07:21.141
♪ So if you need
a private detective

07:21.141 --> 07:23.714
♪ Darryl Parks is your guy

07:23.714 --> 07:25.576
♪ The first 100 callers

07:25.576 --> 07:28.779
♪ Get a free rhubarb pie! ♪

07:31.622 --> 07:34.485
So? What do you think?
 I like it.

07:34.485 --> 07:37.788
But you sure these guys
can make enough pies?

07:40.130 --> 07:41.992
What the heck
is a rhubarb, anyway?

07:41.992 --> 07:44.464
You couldn't
have said apple?

07:50.741 --> 07:52.743
Hey there, future
Wolfpack friend.

07:52.743 --> 07:53.944
Here's your gift.

07:53.944 --> 07:55.706
I think you're going
to love it!

08:03.814 --> 08:05.986
It's kind of girly.

08:07.017 --> 08:09.119
How so?

08:09.119 --> 08:11.762
It says,
"I'm a girly girl."

08:13.624 --> 08:15.125
Plus, I don't think
it will fit me.

08:15.926 --> 08:19.770
Hey, maybe
it would fit me!

08:21.171 --> 08:22.533
(GASPS)

08:22.533 --> 08:25.836
It would! See? Aw!
We're such good friends

08:25.836 --> 08:29.509
we share each
other's clothes!

08:29.509 --> 08:31.882
Cameron, I hope
you like my gift.

08:31.882 --> 08:34.284
I made you a mixtape!

08:34.284 --> 08:38.719
A collection
of songs? Yawn.

08:38.719 --> 08:41.692
What?
No. A mixed tape.

08:42.823 --> 08:44.094
Duct tape,

08:44.094 --> 08:48.258
masking tape,
electrical tape...

08:48.258 --> 08:52.032
All my favorite tapes
are on here!

08:52.032 --> 08:54.204
You've got to be kidding me!

08:54.204 --> 08:59.840
Tape is not a gift!
Tape is what you use
to wrap a gift!

08:59.840 --> 09:03.614
By the way,
I got this police tape
from a really nice cat

09:03.614 --> 09:04.975
who patrols my neighborhood.

09:11.882 --> 09:14.855
I can't believe our ad has
only gotten one view.

09:14.855 --> 09:16.126
And it's a "dislike."

09:18.759 --> 09:19.760
That was me.

09:21.962 --> 09:25.866
Everyone knows sasquatches
have no capacity
for human speech.

09:25.866 --> 09:28.939
And if they did, they'd
have a Canadian accent.

09:30.801 --> 09:34.044
Very shoddy work, Fletcher.

09:34.044 --> 09:37.207
My dad is even more
depressed now
than he was before.

09:37.207 --> 09:39.780
(SIGHS) I got him
into this mess,
so I need to get him out.

09:40.811 --> 09:43.153
We need to find my dad
a mystery to solve.

09:43.153 --> 09:45.716
How about why won't
Chyna love me?

09:46.857 --> 09:49.219
What?

09:49.219 --> 09:51.762
Well, I didn't say anything.

09:51.762 --> 09:52.823
Yeah.

09:54.094 --> 09:56.096
Hey! How about this?

09:56.096 --> 09:58.929
We can hide
something valuable,
report it stolen,

09:58.929 --> 10:00.300
and have him find it.

10:01.071 --> 10:03.273
Good idea.

10:03.273 --> 10:07.738
And I know just
the thing to hide.

10:07.738 --> 10:08.779
Is it your love for me?

10:11.281 --> 10:14.144
What? Who said that?

10:20.020 --> 10:21.792
There.

10:21.792 --> 10:23.994
We'll just stash
these instruments
in the janitor's closet.

10:23.994 --> 10:26.156
Well, won't the
janitor get blamed?

10:26.156 --> 10:30.701
Janitor? When was
the last time you saw
a janitor at this school?

10:30.701 --> 10:33.934
It's perfect.
They're big and shiny
and easy to find.

10:33.934 --> 10:35.906
But most importantly,

10:35.906 --> 10:38.909
now we'll get a break
from listening to you
play the tuba.

10:38.909 --> 10:41.241
What? Who doesn't
like the tuba?

10:45.075 --> 10:46.076
(SIGHS)

10:54.224 --> 10:57.427
What do you think of this
for the plaque on my statue?

10:57.427 --> 10:59.890
"Principal Susan Skidmore.

10:59.890 --> 11:02.793
"Respected, intelligent,

11:02.793 --> 11:04.264
"professional."

11:08.038 --> 11:09.039
Hey!

11:12.943 --> 11:14.244
Principal Skidmore!

11:14.244 --> 11:17.908
All of my brass instruments
are mysteriously missing!

11:17.908 --> 11:19.109
Missing? What do
you mean by missing?

11:23.183 --> 11:24.785
I mean they're gone.

11:24.785 --> 11:26.086
And we need to find them!

11:26.416 --> 11:27.858
But how?

11:27.858 --> 11:30.891
If only there were an
extremely qualified,

11:30.891 --> 11:35.695
reasonably priced,
unlicensed private
investigator we could call.

11:36.696 --> 11:38.328
Wait!

11:38.328 --> 11:41.832
Isn't your father,
ex-police officer
Darryl Parks,

11:41.832 --> 11:43.774
working as a
reasonably priced,

11:43.774 --> 11:46.907
unlicensed private
investigator now?

11:48.478 --> 11:50.981
By Jove, you're right!

11:50.981 --> 11:54.184
We can hire
Chyna's dad!

11:54.184 --> 11:57.117
Why didn't we
think of that?

11:57.117 --> 11:59.049
Well, I guess
it would cost less

11:59.049 --> 12:00.921
than buying
new instruments.

12:00.921 --> 12:03.723
You won't regret this.
 Mmm.
I'm sure I won't.

12:03.723 --> 12:05.155
Hey, wait!

12:05.155 --> 12:06.957
Now give me your lunch.
I'm hungry.

12:19.069 --> 12:21.011
Hey, Cameron,

12:21.011 --> 12:24.374
since we're best friends,
I planned this whole
super fun day for us.

12:24.374 --> 12:28.148
We can go shopping
and get our hair done.

12:28.148 --> 12:31.051
Or you can help me
make a movie.

12:31.051 --> 12:32.923
I need another actress.

12:32.923 --> 12:38.188
Well, I do like acting.
And attention.

12:38.188 --> 12:43.133
Okay, you're the voice
of Agent Sourdough Smith
in my newest masterpiece,

12:43.133 --> 12:46.166
Mission: Impossible
Toast Protocol.

12:47.137 --> 12:49.269
Now here's the scene.

12:49.269 --> 12:51.541
You have to rescue
Ambassador Ciabatta,

12:51.541 --> 12:54.975
who is being held captive by
a radical group of croutons.

13:00.180 --> 13:02.552
And action!

13:02.552 --> 13:06.386
I have got to save
Ambassador Ciabatta
from this jam!

13:06.386 --> 13:10.790
Cut!
You don't sound like toast.
You sound like bread.

13:12.792 --> 13:15.826
We're not making
 Bread Protocol.

13:15.826 --> 13:19.529
Now say it again.
This time, more toasty.
Action!

13:21.801 --> 13:25.375
(IN BRITISH ACCENT) I've got
to save Ambassador Ciabatta
from this jam!

13:25.375 --> 13:27.307
Cut!

13:27.307 --> 13:29.309
The character is not
an English muffin!

13:31.011 --> 13:34.044
Come on, Lexi,
be the toast!

13:36.246 --> 13:39.519
(IN FRENCH ACCENT)
I've got to save the
Ambassador Ciabatta

13:39.519 --> 13:42.022
from this jam!

13:42.853 --> 13:44.524
That was French toast!

13:46.196 --> 13:47.928
I can't work like this.

13:50.230 --> 13:51.902
Crew, that's lunch.

13:58.208 --> 14:00.340
Hey, guys,
how's it going?

14:00.340 --> 14:01.972
That's the voice!

14:01.972 --> 14:05.215
Paisley, you are my toast!

14:05.215 --> 14:07.277
Oh, come on! Really?

14:07.277 --> 14:12.252
Hey, I can't help it
if Paisley sounds
exactly like toast.

14:12.252 --> 14:14.324
I get that a lot.

14:17.988 --> 14:20.230
This is where the tuba
was last seen alive.

14:24.194 --> 14:27.197
Who has access
to this room?

14:27.197 --> 14:34.004
Just the Ants, the janitor,
the teachers, the janitor,
the janitor and the janitor.

14:34.004 --> 14:36.306
Oh, yeah, and
also the janitor.

14:38.078 --> 14:41.151
So it could be anyone.

14:43.313 --> 14:46.386
Well, they wiped their
fingerprints clean,

14:46.386 --> 14:51.421
so it must be someone
with access to rags
and cleaning products

14:51.421 --> 14:55.625
and other
janitorial supplies.

14:55.625 --> 14:59.269
It must be someone
who wears gloves.

15:01.471 --> 15:04.234
All signs point to

15:04.234 --> 15:06.006
a glove model.

15:07.607 --> 15:09.409
Or a mime!

15:09.409 --> 15:12.282
Or a Michael Jackson
impersonator!

15:12.282 --> 15:13.944
Or a janitor!

15:15.645 --> 15:18.318
You're right.
It could be a mime.

15:20.190 --> 15:24.294
You know what?
I think I saw a mime
in the janitor's closet.

15:24.294 --> 15:25.295
Good thinking, Dad.

15:25.295 --> 15:26.556
Let's go.

15:29.659 --> 15:31.361
Amazing, Dad.

15:31.361 --> 15:35.305
Your incredible
detective skills
led us right to the...

15:35.305 --> 15:39.009
Cleaning supplies?
Where are the instruments?

15:39.009 --> 15:41.141
That was my only lead.

15:41.141 --> 15:42.312
I give up.

15:42.312 --> 15:44.414
I'll never catch the culprit.

15:44.414 --> 15:47.017
We should just
call the police.

15:47.017 --> 15:50.580
Here, kitty, kitty, kitty.

15:50.580 --> 15:54.184
Here, kitty, kitty, kitty.

16:01.992 --> 16:03.733
We have to find
those instruments!

16:03.733 --> 16:05.495
The orchestra has
a concert next week

16:05.495 --> 16:07.567
and I'm gonna look
silly doing this.

16:07.567 --> 16:09.669
(MIMICKING TROMBONE)

16:10.700 --> 16:12.642
(LAUGHING)

16:12.642 --> 16:15.305
Look who's in the dorkestra.

16:16.076 --> 16:17.077
(BOTH SIGHING)

16:18.978 --> 16:20.480
Hey.

16:20.480 --> 16:23.583
On cop shows,
they always set a trap
for the criminals.

16:23.583 --> 16:25.655
I'm on it.

16:25.655 --> 16:28.058
Okay, we'll catch
the criminal with
a stakeout.

16:28.058 --> 16:30.760
We just wait here
until he takes the bait
and we swoop in.

16:30.760 --> 16:33.393
Do we really need the van?
 Yes.

16:33.393 --> 16:35.025
This way we're
less conspicuous.

16:38.498 --> 16:40.630
Ha! China left this

16:40.630 --> 16:43.533
very real tuba here
unattended.

16:46.036 --> 16:48.508
Wait, where did that
tuba case come from?

16:50.680 --> 16:52.011
(GASPS)

16:57.617 --> 16:59.219
That's the thief!

16:59.619 --> 17:01.521
Case closed.

17:01.521 --> 17:03.253
What are you talking about
the case is closed?

17:03.253 --> 17:04.723
We don't know
who is in that disguise!

17:04.723 --> 17:08.657
No, I meant that
tuba case is closed.

17:08.657 --> 17:10.660
It opened and
now it's closed.

17:10.660 --> 17:13.031
Okay. Well, then,
why would you use
the words "case closed"?

17:13.031 --> 17:14.664
It's unnecessarily confusing.

17:14.664 --> 17:17.707
I was just trying to say
that we should get out there
and stop him.

17:17.707 --> 17:19.209
Okay, well, maybe
you should just say,

17:19.209 --> 17:21.570
"Let's get out there
and stop him."

17:21.570 --> 17:22.612
It's too late now.

17:24.644 --> 17:25.815
He's gone.

17:27.747 --> 17:29.379
That's not even
the worst part.

17:29.379 --> 17:30.650
We got
a parking ticket!

17:37.457 --> 17:39.759
As you know, I asked
you both to prepare

17:39.759 --> 17:42.162
a tribute to me
and our friendship.

17:42.162 --> 17:44.664
Lexi, you go first.

17:44.664 --> 17:47.697
Cameron, I wrote
a little song for you.

17:47.697 --> 17:51.501
It's not much,
but I hope you like it.

17:57.177 --> 17:59.509
♪ To show you
what you mean to me

17:59.509 --> 18:01.681
♪ I have something
special planned

18:01.681 --> 18:03.753
♪ So give it up, my BFF

18:03.753 --> 18:06.786
♪ For the
Webster Marching Band

18:06.786 --> 18:08.118
(PLAYING MARCH)

18:10.790 --> 18:12.762
♪ Our friendship's real
just like my hair

18:12.762 --> 18:15.265
♪ Paisley's really a brunette

18:15.265 --> 18:17.497
♪ To show you
just how much I care

18:17.497 --> 18:19.699
♪ Here come
these majorettes

18:24.174 --> 18:26.576
♪ I've invited
all these nerds here

18:26.576 --> 18:28.778
♪ To give you my regards

18:28.778 --> 18:30.840
♪ And now we'll see
your smiling face

18:30.840 --> 18:33.343
♪ When they turn
around these cards!

18:35.745 --> 18:37.687
♪ If I had to rate
your awesomeness

18:37.687 --> 18:39.649
♪ I'd give you a perfect 10

18:39.649 --> 18:41.851
♪ So how do I
spell friendship?

18:41.851 --> 18:44.594
♪ C-A-M-E-R-O-N ♪

18:53.703 --> 18:56.566
Okay.
Paisley, your turn.

18:59.869 --> 19:01.511
(BELCHES)

19:03.243 --> 19:04.814
Paisley,

19:04.814 --> 19:07.817
that was the most
beautiful thing
I've ever heard!

19:07.817 --> 19:11.521
Are you joking?
She just burped!

19:11.521 --> 19:14.724
It wasn't just
a burp, Lexi.

19:14.724 --> 19:17.357
It was our burp.

19:17.357 --> 19:19.759
We were both
in second grade.

19:19.759 --> 19:20.860
For the second time.

19:21.731 --> 19:23.593
And on March 29th,

19:23.593 --> 19:25.895
Cameron and I shared
a can of soda
on the jungle gym.

19:25.895 --> 19:30.800
When we were done,
we both burped at
exactly the same time.

19:30.800 --> 19:32.872
I can't believe
you remember that.

19:32.872 --> 19:36.606
Of course. It was
a special moment.

19:36.606 --> 19:37.877
So, from now on,

19:37.877 --> 19:40.750
every March 29th,
we'll share a soda...

19:40.750 --> 19:44.384
BOTH: ...and celebrate
our Burp Day.

19:45.285 --> 19:46.886
(BOTH BELCHING)

19:48.858 --> 19:52.492
You've got to be kidding me!

19:52.492 --> 19:54.824
Okay. I've made my decision.

19:54.824 --> 19:56.596
It's a no-brainer.

19:56.596 --> 19:59.629
From the mixtape, to the
dead-on toast impression,

19:59.629 --> 20:02.502
the person I will friend is...

20:03.433 --> 20:04.534
(KISSING)

20:04.534 --> 20:06.736
Lexi!

20:06.736 --> 20:08.838
Yes, I win!

20:08.838 --> 20:10.910
Play me off, nerds!

20:25.995 --> 20:27.797
And now,
I present to you

20:27.797 --> 20:30.400
a statue of
my personal hero.

20:30.930 --> 20:32.402
Me!

20:37.367 --> 20:39.769
"Principal Susan Skidmore.

20:39.769 --> 20:42.942
"Respected,
intelligent,
professional."

20:44.714 --> 20:46.816
I think the engraver
used an abbreviation.

20:49.479 --> 20:51.821
"R.I.P."?

20:51.821 --> 20:54.924
Oh, I thought
you were just dead
on the inside.

20:56.726 --> 20:58.828
Stop!

20:58.828 --> 21:01.431
I know who took
the instruments!

21:01.431 --> 21:03.533
You do?
 Yes.

21:03.533 --> 21:05.995
It was Principal
Skidmore!

21:05.995 --> 21:07.567
(ALL GASPING)

21:07.567 --> 21:11.000
She stole the instruments
and now I see why.

21:11.000 --> 21:13.773
She melted them
to use the brass

21:13.773 --> 21:16.706
to make this statue of the
Wicked Witch of the West.

21:16.706 --> 21:19.409
That's me.
I did no such thing.

21:19.409 --> 21:21.611
That's utterly ridiculous.

21:21.611 --> 21:23.853
I think my dad's
actually right.

21:25.955 --> 21:27.987
(HORN BLOWING)

21:29.989 --> 21:31.621
Fine. It was me.

21:33.963 --> 21:36.396
Dad, how did you
figure it out?

21:36.396 --> 21:40.900
Well, you always tell me
how incredibly evil
Principal Skidmore is.

21:40.900 --> 21:42.572
In the nicest
possible way.

21:44.003 --> 21:46.776
And how she would
never spend money
for anything but herself.

21:46.776 --> 21:49.008
Again, meant
as a compliment.

21:49.008 --> 21:51.541
So when Principal
Skidmore hired me,

21:51.541 --> 21:53.443
it had to be
part of her plan.

21:53.443 --> 21:56.716
She assumed I was
a terrible detective and
would never solve the case

21:56.716 --> 21:58.888
so she'd get away clean.

21:58.888 --> 22:01.351
But she was wrong.
You solved the case.

22:01.351 --> 22:02.992
(ALL CHEERING)

22:04.724 --> 22:06.426
Nice going, Dad.
 Thanks.

22:10.360 --> 22:14.033
You guys always
give me a hard time about
shooting video of you,

22:14.033 --> 22:15.665
but you look so cute.

22:18.508 --> 22:21.741
I remember that moment.
 Of course you do.

22:21.741 --> 22:24.574
The concert was
20 minutes ago.

22:25.375 --> 22:26.576
Hey,

22:26.576 --> 22:28.478
I'm proud of you.

22:28.478 --> 22:30.950
Oh, here comes your solo!

22:32.982 --> 22:34.754
(PLAYING HORN)

22:39.389 --> 22:41.991
Oh, pass me the remote.

22:41.991 --> 22:46.035
Are you going to show me
the video of us watching
the video we just watched?

22:47.036 --> 22:50.139
No, I still
have to edit that.

22:53.473 --> 22:56.646
Someone
I used to work with
got a TV show.

22:56.646 --> 22:58.708
Really? Who?

